on but also their American-born children, more recent immigrants, and people who married into Iranian families, all of whom carry their own stories of trauma, triumph, adversity, and belonging that reflect varied and nuanced perspectives on what it means to be Iranian or Iranian American. The essays in My Shadow Is My Skin are these stories. This collection brings together thirty-two authors, both established and emerging, whose writing captures the diversity of Iranian diasporic experiences. Reflecting on the Iranian American experience over the past forty years and shedding new light on themes of identity, duality, and alienation in twenty-first-century America, the authors present personal narratives of immigration, sexuality, marginalization, marriage, and religion that offer an antidote to the news media's often superficial portrayals of Iran and the people who have a connection to it. My Shadow Is My Skin illuminates a community that rarely gets to tell its own story.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIranian AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aIranian AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aIranian diaspora. 0aIranianszUnited States. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh1 aAbdoh, Salar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAfrasiabi, Dena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtai, Maryam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtefat-Peckham, Darius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAttaran, Nazanine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaffa, Mandana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCopeland, Cyrus M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarznik, Jasmin, econtributor.4ctb4https: